<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="25.[189,303,1467,1493]" box="[189,303,1467,1493]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1467,1493]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1467,1493]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[189,1400,1514,1611]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
The new species is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="Yeshwanth &amp; Konstantinov, 2021" authorityName="Yeshwanth &amp; Konstantinov" authorityYear="2021" box="[735,881,1515,1540]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="Namyatovia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sirsiensis" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[735,881,1515,1540]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">N. sirsiensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[888,1070,1514,1540]" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
by its more uniform dorsal coloration and striking features of the male genitalia. A peculiar sclerotized outgrowth originating from the extreme base of the aedeagus seems to be a unique feature within eccritotarsines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
